clesall, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Warwick","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Warwick, the county seat of Warwickshire, or from the county itself. The placename derives from Old English <i>wering</i>, <i>wæring</i> ‘dam’ (a derivative of <i>wer</i>, <i>wær</i> ‘weir’) + <i>wīc</i> ‘dwelling, specialized farmstead’ (dative plural <i>wīcum</i>).","habitational name from a much smaller place of the same name in Cumbria. This placename probably derives from Old English <i>waroth</i> ‘bank, shore’ + <i>wīc</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Warrick","meanings":["English:","variant of   Warwick  .","from Middle English <i>warrok</i> ‘wedge or twisting stick used to tighten the lashings on a scaffold’, perhaps a metonymic occupational name for a maker of warrocks or a builder of scaffolds. In the building trades the lashings for scaffolds were tightened by driving in wedges called <i>warrocks</i>."]},{"name":"Worrick","meanings":["English: variant of   Warwick  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":71,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":80,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":115,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Warwick was born in 1144, in Plumpton in Spofforth, Yorkshire, England. He married Ann of Plumpton. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1144–":"1144–Surnud","1148–Female":"1148–Surnud","1170–1213":"1170–1213","1144–Male":"1144–Surnud","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1148":"1148","1224":"1224","1213":"1213","1144":"1144","1170":"1170","Plumpton, Yorkshire, England":"Plumpton by Ecclesall, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1144–":"1144–Kuollut","1148–Female":"1148–Kuollut","1170–1213":"1170–1213","1144–Male":"1144–Kuollut","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1148":"1148","1224":"1224","1213":"1213","1144":"1144","1170":"1170","Plumpton, Yorkshire, England":"Plumpton by Ecclesall, Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"1144–":"1144–Décédé","1148–Female":"1148–Décédée","1170–1213":"1170–1213","1144–Male":"1144–Décédé","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1148":"1148","1224":"1224","1213":"1213","1144":"1144","1170":"1170","Plumpton, Yorkshire, England":"Plumpton by Ecclesall, Everwyck, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Robert de Warwick est né en 1144, à Plumpton in Spofforth, Everwyck, Angleterre. Il a épousé Ann of Plumpton. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille."},"de":{"1144–":"1144–Verstorben","1148–Female":"1148–Verstorben","1170–1213":"1170–1213","1144–Male":"1144–Verstorben","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1148":"1148","1224":"1224","1213":"1213","1144":"1144","1170":"1170","Plumpton, Yorkshire, England":"Plumpton by Ecclesall, Yorkshire, England","lifeSummary":"Robert de Warwick wurde 1144 in Plumpton in Spofforth, Yorkshire, England geboren. Er hat Ann of Plumpton geheiratet. Sie hatten mindestens 1 Tochter."},"ht":{"1144–":"1144–Desede","1148–Female":"1148–Desede","1170–1213":"1170–1213","1144–Male":"1144–Desede","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1148":"1148","1224":"1224","1213":"1213","1144":"1144","1170":"1170","Plumpton, Yorkshire, England":"Plumpton by Ecclesall, Yorkshire, England"},"hu":{"1144–":"1144–elhunyt","1148–Female":"1148–elhunyt","